## 1. Document Control and Authority
This manual establishes the student-facing operating standard for the OPRMT™ certification program.

- Applies to enrolled students, reviewers, instructors, and administrators working within the current certification edition.
- Assumes a ten-module learning path aligned to the OPRMT™ framework and associated compliance expectations.
- Controls student conduct, assessment logic, submission standards, certificate issuance, and permitted credential use.
- Should be read together with the current curriculum map, assignment instructions, and program notices.

## 2. Program Purpose and Credential Scope
The certification program is designed to train students to engineer prompts and prompt systems as structured technical assets rather than ad hoc text inputs.

- Teach students to apply the OPRMT™ framework in a repeatable, auditable manner.
- Develop operational skill in defining objectives, constraints, output requirements, procedures, and tool chains.
- Train students to produce outputs that are versioned, testable, and suitable for business or technical deployment.
- Introduce certification-level discipline in documentation, reproducibility, compliance, and evidence-based evaluation.

## 3. Expected Student Outcomes
By the end of the program, a successful student should be able to:

- Translate an abstract request into a structured OPRMT™ prompt with explicit assumptions and enforceable requirements.
- Differentiate concept, framework, implementation, and execution within a prompt-driven workflow.
- Create prompts that specify acceptable outputs, failure conditions, validation criteria, and tool usage rules.
- Produce documentation and deliverables suitable for client work, internal use, product packaging, or public release.
- Defend prompt design decisions using structure, rationale, and evidence instead of intuition alone.

## 4. Certification Architecture
The certification pathway is organized as a staged learning system. Each module has its own lesson, worksheet, and evidence requirements.

| Module | Title | Primary Competency | Required Deliverables |
|---|---|---|---|
| M0 | Orientation and Foundations | Program rules, terminology, student workflow, workspace setup | Orientation acknowledgment, setup checklist |
| M1 | Objective Engineering | Translate requests into clear goals, scope, and success conditions | Objective worksheet, rewritten prompt objective block |
| M2 | Parameters Engineering | Define constraints, variables, inputs, exclusions, and guardrails | Parameter matrix, constrained prompt build |
| M3 | Results Engineering | Specify desired outputs, schemas, quality thresholds, and acceptance tests | Output definition sheet, acceptance criteria |
| M4 | Method Engineering | Sequence procedure, logic, reasoning flow, validation, and correction steps | Method design worksheet, procedural prompt |
| M5 | Tools Engineering | Declare tools, sources, model behaviors, and execution dependencies | Tooling plan, model/tool integration prompt |
| M6 | Prompt Assembly and Architecture | Assemble complete multi-part prompts and reusable system assets | Integrated OPRMT™ prompt package |
| M7 | Prompt Compliance Engineering Introduction | Evaluate structure, compliance, traceability, and policy fit | Compliance review worksheet, remediation notes |
| M8 | Applied Systems Execution | Deploy OPRMT™ in real workflows, operations, products, or client scenarios | Applied scenario build, evidence log |
| M9 | Capstone and Final Review | Demonstrate end-to-end competency and defend design choices | Capstone package, final review submission |

## 5. Student Operating Standards
Students are expected to operate with professional discipline throughout the program.

- Follow the current assignment instructions exactly and use the required naming conventions.
- Submit work in the required format, with evidence of revision where revision is requested.
- Label assumptions, dependencies, external tools, and unsupported claims explicitly.
- Protect confidential, proprietary, or client-sensitive information at all times.
- Maintain version control over their own work and keep source files for audit or review when requested.

## 6. Assessment and Progression Model
Certification is performance-based. Completion alone is not sufficient; the student must meet the defined quality threshold.

| Assessment Element | Weight | What Is Evaluated | Minimum Standard |
|---|---:|---|---|
| Orientation Completion | Required gate | Program rules acknowledged; workspace and templates prepared | Must be complete before graded progression |
| Module Quizzes | 20% | Core terminology, framework logic, standards, and application rules | 80% minimum average |
| Worksheets and Labs | 30% | Component-level execution and structured reasoning evidence | Passing across required modules |
| Practical Prompt Builds | 25% | Operational prompt construction and revision quality | Reviewer-approved quality threshold |
| Final Exam | 10% | Integrated knowledge verification across the framework | 85% minimum |
| Capstone | 15% | End-to-end system build, evidence, and defense | Approval required; no critical violations |

## 7. Submission and Artifact Standards
Student work is evaluated as an engineered artifact. Every submission must be readable, reproducible, and properly packaged.

| Requirement | Student Rule |
|---|---|
| File Naming | Use module code, asset type, and version number in the filename |
| Metadata | State use case, intended audience, target model or tool, and version |
| Traceability | Show how the final output maps back to objective, parameters, and results |
| Reproducibility | Include method steps, test inputs, and any critical execution notes |
| Professional Format | Deliver readable, organized files suitable for review or client handoff |

## 8. Academic Integrity and Approved AI Use
This program teaches AI work; therefore AI use is permitted only within the assignment rules and must not replace student accountability.

- Students may use approved AI tools for drafting, testing, comparison, and iteration when the assignment allows it.
- Students remain responsible for final accuracy, structure, originality, and compliance.
- Undisclosed copying, resale of another person's work, fabricated validation, or false performance claims are prohibited.
- Where assistance materially shaped the result, the student must disclose the tool or source and the role it played.

### Critical Integrity Violations
- Submitting another person's work as your own
- Falsifying test results, scores, or review history
- Using undisclosed assistance where disclosure was required
- Claiming certification before formal issuance
- Using the credential to imply unauthorized affiliation or authority

## 9. Capstone and Final Certification Review
The capstone functions as the final demonstration of competency. It must prove that the student can build and defend a complete OPRMT™ system under review.

- The capstone must solve a real or realistic business, technical, operational, or educational problem.
- The final package must include the prompt system, supporting rationale, validation approach, and resulting outputs.
- Reviewers may require revision, resubmission, or oral or written clarification before approving certification.
- A capstone that is operationally impressive but structurally noncompliant does not pass by default.

## 10. Certificate Issuance and Credential Use
Certificates are issued only after all mandatory requirements have been satisfied and final review has been approved.

| Use Category | Policy |
|---|---|
| Permitted Uses | Resume listings, bios, portfolios, proposals, service pages, and internal capability records using the exact approved credential title. |
| Restricted Uses | Implying legal licensure, regulatory certification, corporate partnership, agency authority, or ownership rights not separately granted. |
| Prohibited Uses | Editing the certificate, selling the credential itself, misreporting version status, or claiming certification before issuance. |
| Version Rule | The holder should reference the certification edition or framework version when material to the claim or engagement. |

## 11. Support, Communications, and Student Records
Program operations require clean communication and reliable recordkeeping.

- Students should use the official support channel for administrative, technical, or certification questions.
- Feedback and review notes should be preserved as part of the student's working record when revisions are required.
- Students are responsible for retaining their own copies of submissions, evidence, and final approved deliverables.
- The program may maintain records related to enrollment, submissions, assessment, issuance status, and disciplinary decisions.

